## M22.1(6/8): inline `zig "..."` raw-Zig escape is reserved in V1.
##
## Per GPT-5.5 entry 39 (M22.1 "fake-surface audit"): the grammar
## accepted `zig "..."` (a string literal interpreted as raw Zig
## source to splice into emit), parser built `(zig "...")` IR,
## sema walked it cleanly — but emit had no handler. It fell
## through to `@compileError("rig: emitter does not yet support
## zig")`. Same fake-surface anti-pattern as `try_block` and
## `pre_block`: the user sees a Zig compile error inside Rig-
## generated code instead of a Rig diagnostic.
##
## V1 escape-valves (kept):
##   - `raw INDENT body OUTDENT` — audit boundary for `%x` raw
##     access + non-whitelisted builtins
##   - `extern` declarations       — FFI boundary at the symbol
##     level; calls require `raw` block at call site
##   - `@builtin(...)` calls       — default-unsafe + safe-list
##     for compile-time type introspection
##
## Inline Zig text is qualitatively different — it embeds a
## second language in the first, with no story for scope
## capture, symbol hygiene, ownership effects, or audit
## boundaries. If it returns in V2+, it needs a serious design
## pass and probably a different syntactic surface (e.g., a
## dedicated `extern` body form).

sub main()
  zig "const x = 42; std.debug.print(\"{any}\\n\", .{x});"
